Home Dec 25, 1854
Dear Sister Anna,
I have but little time to write this evening, and moreover I believe I am not in debt to you, - but think I must write a little letter "[??] - A letter from Isaac came last Saturday - He writes that he hopes to get away immediately after the 26th - and will return by way of Elyria- Says he may be obliged to stop some days in Chicago - and in New York City also, it may be - I do hope not long, for you can imagine I suppose that I am impatient to see him - These last weeks do seem so long - But have I not every thing to make me glad and thankful? If he only comes at last, safe and well, and finds us in health, what more can I ask? Isaac said Charles was coming by way of 
Written along the left side:
I am just finishing a little [?] dress for Mayo - Dark red

He mean [??] I drawers - short dresses of common print aprons with long sleeves - outdoors about

every day -
Completed

your house too - I suppose you have seen him long before this, and that he is now in Milo [?] - What a happy family they must be - Albina will think her troubles are all ended. I have good news from Bangor & Emile frequently - I should like to step in and sit with mother and Lucy some of these afternoons - Isn't it good that dear little Percie is so well. I am longing to see him and the little "G.E.M" - I like the name now better than the first. Do not you? Sallie must enjoy the winter much with both her sisters. I am glad they can be with her - She is a dear Sallie I think.
How are Hattie & Libbie this winter and what are they doing? A great deal of love to them - I wonder if you have had any cold weather this winter? We have, and snow besides - It is piled up splendidly all about us, and I do delight to see it - The drifts are in
Completed

every imaginable shape - steeples & towers and palaces - now a smooth surface, and now like the waves of ocean - I do love to look at them - I have seen the same hundreds of times before, but it all seems new, this winter, and more than ever beautiful - perhaps because I've been two winters where the snow is minimal, and they have mud instead.
Mayo has attained must since you saw him - He is usually very well & running about every where - He is handy still from morning till night - has one little nap - seldom more than one hour and oftener less.
Isaac writes that you have been enjoying a visit from the son living in Peru with his family - You must have been quite busy I think - I hope you are all well - I shall hear all about you by Isaac, when he comes. Is "Lottie" well? I should love to be better acquainted with her - I enclose
Completed

with this a letter for Isaac - I presume it will reach Elyria in season for him -
I haste, but with much love to you all,
Sister Nettie

written upside down , a name begging Mrs.

Nettie P. Metcalf
to Anna M Metcalf
for 1858
Elyria, Ohio
Saturday Eve. Nov. 13, 1858
My dear mother,-
It seems a long time since I have myself written to you - indeed I have not written many letters of late to any one. but I have thought of you and loved you all the while. I am all alone with the children this evening. Isaac is down town, the girls are out and Rollin down to his uncle's to see his sick mother. Willie [?] is sleeping nicely, but Charly wakes every few moments - he has taken some cold, and finds it hard to breathe easily. It does seem strange to see our baby Charly trudging about the house on his own feet - We have
Completed

hardly become accustomed to it yet, though he seems quite at home himself - [?] delights to lead him about - makes him go too fast and fall sometimes. We went to Cleveland last week - bought Wilder [?] a regular little over coat; drab, trimmed with drab velvet - got him too, a box of lettered blocks, which seemed to take his mind more than the coat. He tried the coat on, walked about a little and then said, "Well now, let's take it off, and lay it away in the drawer." He has not sucked his thumb since these things came. He says, "I used to suck my thumb, when I was a little boy; but I'm a big boy now, and don't suck it a bit." He wanted to know the other day if Jesus Christ went
Completed

right straight up into heaven, when he went away from the Earth, and if the [?] cover was up, so that he did'nt (sic) bump his head. He is very full of questions Anna & I have some new furs. She will tell you about them, I suppose - bought at Cleveland for $52.50 - Tippet & cuffs never sold before for less than $65,00. We did not get muffs - They would have been $10,00 extra - I am dreading to wear mine - If I had my old ones, I was saying to Isaac, I should have worn them several times before now, & the prospect is for a very cold day tomorrow - It is very cold this evening - Isaac has come He says the Dr told Anna if she did not wear her furs tomorrow, she should not go to
Completed

meeting with him. We talk of having a sewing machine together, Anna and I - I have been very busy indeed sewing - Charly wore out two or three dresses entirely while creeping - I have finished two [?] ones for him A blue, out of the two blue ones he wore last winter and the crimson & black that was Libby's - Like Percy's waist. And have two more thicker ones partly made. Wilder wears sacks & pants - Has three every day sack aprons - one handsome plaid sack - These, with their under clothing, and various mending & making for the rest of us have kept me employed - I am making one sack and cape for Charly now - outside garment. It is a crimson & black, plaid of camel
Completed

I only want to tell you one or two of Wilder's sayings - A few nights ago he did not feel very well, and was told he could ask God to make him better Next morning he was about as well as ever - He was asked if he had thanked God for making him well. He looked up with a very pleased face and said "There He did, did'nt (sic) He."
Night before last - he was walking on the verandah with me, while I wheeled baby to sleep in the carriage - Isaac & Jenny both go e to meeting. He took his thumb out of his mouth, and pointed up, and said "that is the sky, way up there - Are God & good people up there"? Pretty soon he said, "I should'nt (sic) dare to die - said it two or three
Completed

times before I understood him - I asked him why - He said "because I could not walk there, and I should'nt (sic) be here - I should be way off - I do'nt (sic) know what made him talk so, unless he was remembering what was told him when the little Road children died - that they were dead and buried up in the ground and could'nt (sic) see their father and mother here any more. He begins to ask many questions.
Jenny is going to leave us in the course of a month - She is studying arithmetic at home now.
A great amount of love to Almeda, Lissie & James - I should so love to have them near us - Perhaps it may be so - Charley calls-
Lovingly, Nettie
Charly can say Papa & Mama-
Completed

Dear Charlie -
I thank you and Wilder [?] greatly for your letters - I meant to write to you, this time, but I must let it go till next time, for the letter must go to the office - Will you kiss Anna & John for me? I think you & Wilder will be the very best of boys now mother is gone - Do you get your clothes torn much?
Completed

Dunbarton, Jan. 19, 1850.
Will my friend please accept my thanks for the beautiful and valuable book just presented? I had never seen it before. It will certainly afford much pleasure and instruction in connection with the perusal of Shakspeare (sic) - I do not progress very rapidly in reading Shakspeare (sic) as my time for reading is quite limited at present. I have been absent from home so much, that now, parents, brothers and sister claim considerable of my time. And besides, I am reading each play twice, and now shall add to this Mrs. Jamison's "Characteristics." - The art of discerning between the good and bad, in the books we read, is of great importance; is it not sometimes a very difficult thing - So often does error appear in the garb of truth, and so much buried truth is there, amidst the rubbish of error.
The feelings expressed in your letter are reciprocated. If visiting me, or writing to me, can increase, in any degree your enjoyment, I should be happy to have you do so. I do not expect to find friends
Completed

perfect in mind or manners, and often wonder when considering my own defects, why kind Heaven has granted me so many and so worthy ones. But it is my part to be grateful for them, and endeavor always to merit their esteem, and profit by their superiority. Your manners and conversation, if now, as you have expressed it, but half formed, promise much for the future, - But what are they to this "warm, true heart within"? Far more delightful is it, to "find" and "stir its depths" than to admire pleasing manners, or imposing address. I know full well in my own experience, what it is to feel much more than shrinking nature will permit me to express, by word or act. Can we not, in this respect, make mutual allowance? And in this I do most certainly feel that your charity and forbearance will be far the most severely tasked. Should you know me better, as I am willing should be the case if you desire it to be so, I am sure you will discover much, I fear ore than you think, to be corrected and forgiven.
Shall be happy to hear from you, and to see you, whenever convenient.
Antoinette -
Completed

Dunbarton, March 14, 1850 -
My dear friend,
I welcomed your letter this afternoon, in the midst of whitewashing and papering, and of course, left everything and ran away to read it. - I think you were very kind to write so speedily - I was hoping to hear from you to day, but tried not to expect too strongly, lest, with your many duties, you should be obliged to delay. I am very glad you succeeded in performing your part of the service at Newport, so pleasantly to yourself and so satisfactorily to all. Mr. Chase is much favored in having an aid in whom he can so safely confide. The Report you sent came to day. I certainly hope the Road will be completed, and that you will remain in New Hampshire, so that we may often have the pleasure of your society.
Probably you re now enjoying much, in the society f treasured friends - mother, sisters, brothers and perhaps others. Hope you find your brother im
written up the left side:
as I would have it. But it seemed as great an act - so mighty in its consequences - they might reach through time and through eternity - But I have asked for aid and for direction and I doubt not you have done so. And when I think of this, I can but feel sure that all will be well - A letter, or your presence would be very welcome. Quite a long letter this. I usually write more than I think I shall when I commence
Truly -
Your Antoinette
Completed

proving in health. Mother thinks she knows somewhat how to sympathize with him -
The afternoon after you left here, my brother and I, very suddenly decided to go to Epsom and Barnstead, to visit an uncle at E - and a school mate of mine, at the latter place. We left home about two o'clock, and arrived at uncle's residence, at six in the evening. At three o'clock, Wednesday afternoon, we started for Barnstead, where we found ourselves after a pleasant ride of about 15 miles - Brother G[?] intended to return home Thursday, and leave me to come by stage, but the storm prevented his returning until Friday and in consequence of this, I thought it better for me to come home with him, - So we were both back again Friday night. We had long contemplated this little journey, and have finally accomplished it. My father was once settled in Epsom, and it is my native place.
Since I came home, I have been rather more busy than usual, in household matters. Mother and I are having considerable to do for brother, before he goes away, which will be in a week or two. - [?] has been papering and whitewashing the room we live in, and I helped him about it, all I could. We are just nicely through with it.
Completed

March 16 - My letters are often somewhat in the journal style - I seldom finish one with a single date, especially when at home.
This is a very clear and beautiful day, and I have just been out to enjoy its sunshine, but it is not very pleasant walking, for the snow is rapidly taking its departure, and it is, of course, rather wet - I was quite glad to get back to the house.
I have engaged to teach a small school about two miles away, which is to commence the 20th of May, and continue 10 weeks, and perhaps a week or two longer. I thought of your advice to me, when I gave my affirmative answer, but this is so near home, that father and mother seemed to favor it, and on the whole I think it better for me to take it. -- Mrs. Parker and Mrs. Chase called here last Sunday - Mrs. P - came to know if I would teach a private school in Goffstown, before the summer term commenced. I hardly think, however, they will succeed in obtaining sufficient scholars, and I rather hope they will not; though it would be a very pleasant school for me - I think I should enjoy it.
- I hope you may realize fully all the happiness that you have been imagining. I almost tremble when I think what I have said and done - not that I regret it, or would retract one word; for it is all
Completed

Goffstown April 6, 1849-
My dear friend,-
My first duty this morning shall be to commence a reply to your good, kind letter. As my date tells you, I am at Goffstown, and this day will close the third week of my school here. The very day I mailed my letter to you, I received a line from G- stating that efforts to obtain scholars had been successful, and desiring me to commence school the next week Tuesday. ( teach 19) Accordingly, I came hither, and began with 28 scholars,- the number is now increased to 38. There have been 41 different ones. This is twice the number I expected, or cared to have, - but probably some of the older ones will leave, as the farmer's spring work advances - Spring seemed early here, when this week commenced - the ground was almost entirely bare, and in some places the grass began to look green - but we have since had quite a snow storm. Not very much, however, now remains on the ground,- but the travelling is very rough
April 16. 1850
Written up the left side:
I expect school here will close the 10 day of hay - I shall board [?] three more places probably - Mr. P[?] the rest is difficult to make out
Completed

and bad - neither sleighing nor wheeling - A wonder time could not be, for school - but the scholars have been very regular thus far - more so than I had any idea they would be, at this season.
I am boarding now, at Mr. Brooks Hadey's. This is the house nearest to school - I may be here all the time, but when I came, I expected to board at three or four places - The travelling is such, that it is better for me to be near - They are so kind as to carry me, even this short distance, some of the time - My school is pleasant, and I am much interested in it - O how great a teacher's responsibility - Certainly no one more needs aid which Earth can never afford - I never felt this more, and I do hope I may be the means of doing some good, not merely to the minds, but to the precious, immortal souls of those with whom I daily mingle - But it is almost nine o'clock, and I must hie me away to my school room duties - I have some lessons to look over a little this morning-
(Evening.) My task is done, for the day and for the week, - and now I come to talk again with you. I did hope to have gone home to night - to spend the Sabbath, but am obliged to relinquish the idea. Mother wrote me yesterday, that Father would
Completed

come for me next Friday, as there will be no school next Saturday.
I was very much interested in your account of the little band of Christians at Milo and their meetings. A blessing must attend them, if they continue to persevere amidst so much to discourage - may they never be" weary in well doing" - I think I never before heard Mr. Willy preach as well as now. Perhaps his many trials have proved blessings in disguise - The people have been making some extra effort to retain him, and I presume he does not now think of leaving.
There is, at present, a vacation in the Sabbath School. Miss Jameson's class, however, continue their recitations, - and one other class, - of little girls. Mrs. Blaisdell has taken Miss Jameson's place since she left town.
I have just been writing a negative reply to a letter, received yesterday, from Sockport, Ills. containing a request to me to return, and take charge of the same school I left - two years since - Perhaps you will see the letter sometime, so I'll not write much about it.-
I was sorry to know that your brother was no better - but how pleasant it is for you, and
Completed

your friends, that he endures what must be a great affliction, with so much fortitude. I do hope he will yet be fully resorted.
Miss Cook, the young lady who had been sick so long - of whom you heard us speak when you were last at D- died just three weeks since. It is just three weeks to day, since I assisted in arraying for the tomb, her lifeless body, - the frail casket - whence a priceless jewel had so recently departed - It was the first time I ever aided in a duty so mournful, and I hope it did me good - I should be sorry if it did not - Death never before seemed to me so solemn a reality - Miss C- was uniformly cheerful, through her sickness, and seemed happy and resigned, [?] the last moment - she took her Father's hands just before she died, and said to him, "Father, I am going, and I'm willing" - I have thought many times since, how full of meaning were those words.
I am reading "Washington and His Generals" now, but I make slow progress - find very little time to read.
You recollect, perhaps that Jack Frost assailed my rose bush, a number of times last Winter, and made it look very disconsolate - I wish you could see it now - it has two beautiful little buds -
I had almost forgotten to tell you that I had a nice ride in the cars to Manchester, about a week since I enjoyed it much - there were 52 persons in the car that morning, I believe -
I need not tell you that I should be happy to see you, or, if this may not be at present; to hear from you again -
Yours ever-
Antoinette-
